def fun_fillna_enc(df_name,df,y_col,cat_c,num_fillna,num_c): 
  # separate target and features
  df_target =df[y_col].copy().reset_index(drop=True)
  df_features = df.drop(y_col, axis=1)
  # Separate numeric and categorical predictors
  df_num_features = df_features.select_dtypes(exclude=['object'])
  df_cat_features = df_features.select_dtypes(include=['object'])
  # impute categorical nan with cat_c, e.g., cat_c ='none'
  df_cat_features = df_cat_features.fillna(cat_c)
  # if num_fillna = 'a', then use column mean to replace numerical nan
  # if num_fillna = 'm' uses column medium to replace numerical nan
  # if num_fillna = 'c', uses num_c, e.g. num_c = -99, to replace numerical nan or nafill(num_c)
  if (num_fillna == 'c'): df_num_features = df_num_features.fillna(num_c).reset_index(drop=True)
  elif (num_fillna == 'a'):
    for i in df_num_features.columns:
      df_num_features.update(df_num_features[i].fillna(value=df_num_features[i].mean(), inplace=True))
  elif (num_fillna == 'm'):
    df_num_features.update(df_num_features[i].fillna(value=df_num_features[i].median(), inplace=True))
  else: print('Invalid num_fillna input\n')

  # Create a transformer object and fit it to cat_features    
  enc = OneHotEncoder(dtype=np.int8)
  enc_f = enc.fit(df_cat_features)
  # Print dummy variable names. Original cat names are lost.
  print(f'Dummy variable names for {df_name}\n')
  print(enc_f.get_feature_names(),'\n')
  mat = enc_f.transform(df_cat_features)
  # mat is a numpy sparse matrix. Transform it to pandas sparse dataframe
  df_cat_enc = pd.DataFrame.sparse.from_spmatrix(mat).reset_index(drop=True)
  # Join the sparse dataframe of dummy variables with the data frame of numeric features
  # reset_index in the two concatenated columns (or use merge on 'TransactionID')
  df_features_enc = pd.concat([df_cat_enc,df_num_features],axis=1)
  print(f'The encoded {df_name} has {df_features_enc.shape[0]} rows, {df_features_enc.shape[1]} columns\n')
  return df_features_enc, df_target;

  def fun_split_dist(df_name,df_features_enc, df_target, test_pct): 
    # split the predictors and the target data frame into test (test_pct) and 
    # train (1-test_pct) dataframes using the target data frame
    # Specify either train_size or test_size is sufficient. 
    # You can change random_state to seed the random number generator differently
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = \
    train_test_split(df_features_enc, df_target, test_size=test_pct, random_state=42)
    # Generate y_counts in train and test sets 
    train_y_counts = y_train.value_counts()
    test_y_counts = y_test.value_counts()
    # print y distribution in percentage and frequency for train and test sets
    print(f'In {df_name} train set ({(1-test_pct)*100}%):','\n')
    for i in y_levels:
      print(f'{round(100*data_y_counts[i]/X_train.shape[0],2)}% or {data_y_counts[i]} instances belong to class {i}','\n')
    #
    print(f'In {df_name} test set ({(test_pct)*100}%):','\n')
    for i in y_levels:
      print(f'{round(100*data_y_counts[i]/X_test.shape[0],2)}% or {data_y_counts[i]} instances belong to class {i}','\n')
    return X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test;

def fun_prc_clf(clf,clf_name,X_train, y_train,X_test,y_test):
  clf_f = clf.fit(X_imb_train,y_imb_train)
  y_pred_prob_train = clf_f.predict_proba(X_train)[:,1]
  y_pred_prob_test = clf_f.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
  ap_train = round(average_precision_score(y_train, y_pred_prob_train,pos_label=1),2)
  precision_train, recall_train, thresholds_train = precision_recall_curve(y_train, y_pred_prob_train, pos_label=[1])
  auprc_train = round(metrics.auc(recall_train, precision_train),2)
  plt.plot(recall_train, precision_train, marker='.',label=f'ap_train={ap_train}, auprc_train={auprc_train}')
  # roc evaluated via test set
  ap_test = round(average_precision_score(y_test, y_pred_prob_test,pos_label=1),2)
  precision_test, recall_test, thresholds_test = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_pred_prob_test, pos_label=1)
  auprc_test = round(metrics.auc(recall_test, precision_test),2)
  plt.plot(recall_test, precision_test, marker='.',color='r',label=f'ap_test={ap_test}, auprc_test={auprc_test}')
  # axis labels
  plt.xlabel('Recall')
  plt.ylabel('Precision')
  plt.title(f'Precision-Recall Curves of {clf_name} evaluated with train and test sets')
  plt.legend() # draw the label in plt.plot()
  # show the plot
  plt.show()

Model Recommendation and Explaination

I’d highly recommend the DTC with depth level 8 as compared to 4. There are several reasons but before that I’d like to discuss my approach. I think for the False -ve are going to be more critical that False +ve because it’s fine we identified a non-fraudulent transaction as fraud but vice versa will hamper profits and be more costly to the company. Keeping this in my mind I immediately hopped on to the confusion matrix and found the DTC 4 and DTC 8 to be the closest but when I took precision and recall into account I realized that recall of DTC 8 is better than DTC 4 with a higher precision. I further went to study if there are any trade offs that I needed to consider. I observed that precision for Random Forest is too high but because the Recall was just 8%. I decided to trade of its precision with Decision Tree depth 8.

This project when deployed will help recall cases better with stronger precisions in short there are higher chances of predicting a fraud trans correctly when the batch of data is feed into the model. I picked up the ap(Avg Precision) and auprc(Area under the Precision Recall Curve) to understand the correlation between the ap and the auprc. It’s alot more clear how in when validated auprc and ap are quiet close and yet the auprc value is greater than the ap and after considering the cost array and calculating avg net benefit both highly lean towards picking DTC 8 over Random Forest, Logistic Regression, DTC 4.
